    <h3>Who Buys Full XL Mattresses?</h3>

    <p>We see Full XL mattresses in a few specific situations:</p>

    <ol>
        <li><strong>Taller Sleepers Who Don't Have Room for a Queen</strong> — You're over 6' tall and need the 80" length, but you don't have room for a Queen's extra 6" of width. Full XL gives you Queen/King length in a smaller footprint.</li>
        <li><strong>Medical Facilities, Dorms, and Camp Settings</strong> — XL lengths (Twin XL and Full XL) are common in hospitals, assisted living, and dormitories. Space is limited but the mattress needs to fit adults of all heights.</li>
        <li><strong>RV and Camper Owners</strong> — Many RVs come with Full XL beds, especially in larger Class A motorhomes. The factory mattress is almost always junk.</li>
        <li><strong>Guest Rooms and Cottages</strong> — When you need to accommodate taller guests but the room is too small for a Queen.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>The Full XL Mattress Problem</h3>

    <p>Here's the issue: when your Full XL mattress wears out, you can't just walk into a mattress store and buy a replacement. Most retailers don't stock this size. The salesperson might not even know it exists.</p>

    <p>So people do one of two things:</p>

    <p><strong>Option 1:</strong> Keep sleeping on their old mattress way past its lifespan. We've removed Full XL mattresses that were 10-15+ years old. The owners knew it was bad. They just didn't know where to find a replacement.</p>

    <p><strong>Option 2:</strong> Buy whatever they can find — usually from a medical supply catalog or RV parts site. Those options are typically thin, cheap pieces of foam that break down quickly and aren't comfortable.</p>

    <p><strong>The good news:</strong> Quality Full XL mattresses exist from the same brands that make mattresses people sleep on for over a decade in their homes. You just have to know where to look.</p>
</section>

<!-- Before You Buy -->
<section id="before-you-buy">
    <h2>Before You Buy: Check Your Bed Frame</h2>

    <p>Before ordering a new Full XL mattress, there are critical things you need to check.</p>

    <h3>Your Full XL Frame Matters More Than You Think</h3>

    <p>Full XL bed frames are hard to find. Because of this, people hold onto their frames forever — sometimes for decades. The problem is that frames break down over time, and <strong>a damaged frame will ruin your new mattress.</strong></p>

    <p><strong>Check your frame's structural integrity:</strong></p>

    <p>We've seen it countless times: someone buys a new mattress, puts it on their old frame, and the mattress starts sagging within months. The frame was the problem all along.</p>

    <p>Here's what to inspect:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Support rails:</strong> Are they bent, cracked, or wobbly? Tighten all screws and bolts.</li>
        <li><strong>Center support:</strong> Does your frame have adequate center support? Full XL at 54" wide may or may not have one — if it does, make sure it's solid.</li>
        <li><strong>Slats:</strong> If your frame uses slats, check each one. Replace any that are cracked or broken. Slats should be no more than 3-4" apart.</li>
        <li><strong>Corner brackets:</strong> These tend to work loose over years of use. Tighten them.</li>
    </ul>

