    <h2>What to Avoid When Buying a Full XL Mattress</h2>

    <div class="red-flags">
        <h3>Red Flags We've Seen</h3>

        <p><strong>1. Cheap Amazon/Walmart "Bed in a Box" Options</strong></p>
        <p>The random no-name brands selling Full XL mattresses for $150-200 are using the cheapest possible materials. We've torn these open — the foam is low-density, the construction is minimal, and they break down fast. You'll be replacing it in 2-3 years.</p>

        <p><strong>2. Medical Catalog Mattresses</strong></p>
        <p>These are thin pieces of foam designed to be cheap, not comfortable. They're meant to be functional, not restful. If you're sleeping on one every night, upgrade to a real mattress.</p>

        <p><strong>3. RV Dealer "Upgrades"</strong></p>
        <p>Even if an RV dealer sells a "premium" or "upgraded" mattress, it's almost never from an actual mattress brand. It's a slightly better piece of foam with a markup. Buy direct from mattress manufacturers instead.</p>

        <p><strong>4. Standard Full Mattresses on Full XL Frames</strong></p>
        <p>This might seem obvious, but we've seen it: a standard Full mattress (54×75) placed on a Full XL frame (54×80), leaving 5 inches of unsupported frame at the foot. Don't do this.</p>
